{"/service/ndnp/mimtptc/batch_mimtptc_dexter_ver01/data/42047197/00340588678/1945090101/0327.xml":{"full_text":"September l s 1945\nDEMANDS OPEN FOR 30% WAGE INCREASE\nTHE DOUBLE STANDARD\nf But how much\nare they FOMMOMW?)\nV Aft*r \u00ab\u00bbC my tots **yj O\nwfff \u2022nifniiT/\nffigyllkg\nY-J Day Brings Showdown\nOn U. 5. Wane, Price Policy\n(From the I'AW Container Burma)\nWASHINGTON \u2014With the ar\nrival of V-J Day, the showdown\nhas come on government stabiliza\ntion policy.\nThe official policy on wage in\ncreases now is that wherever price\nceilings will not be endangered,\ncollective bargaining will be re\nstored. No wage increase will be\ngranted which will result in a price\nincrease.\nReally, however, much of the\nwage policy remains in a vacuum,\ndue to the fact that OPA is sit\nting on the wage lid much more\nheavily than it sits on the price\nlid.\n\nOFFICIALLY, wages are not In\nthe OPA bailiwick. Actually, how\never, OPA is the strongest force\nin Washington opposing a general\nwage increase. By providing em\nployers with the means of turning\nalmost any wage rise into higher\nprice ceilings, OPA gives an infla\ntionary twist to the wage increases\nwhich labor is demanding to offset\nlower take-home and to prevent\ndeflation.\nWar Labor Board chooses to ig\nnore this fact, insisting that wage\npolicy must be decided apart from\nprice policy. But the top stabilizers\nrefuse to approve general wage\nincreases that result in higher\nprices.\nAt the heart of this self-sty\nr S tot/\nI.\u00ab1>\u00abJ\nin\ntJAoring the I A,\nAMERICAN RE- XwMyl\nVOLUTION. THE JEMS/!:\nMERCHANTS\nAMD TNI BIG v rW\nLANDOWNERS JOE WORKER\nWERE DRIVED..\nAS MANY WANTED TO REMAIN\nUNDER ENGLISH RULE AS TO\nBREAK AWAY BUT THIS WAS\nNOT me CASE WITH THE\nWORKERS amp mechanics\nJHEY BACKED THE REVOLU\nTION /ooy, they demand\ned CERTAIN INALIENABLE\nRIGHTS... THE RIGHTS OP\nLIRE, LIBERTY. AND THE PUR\nSUIT OP HAPPINESS TO GAIN\nTHESE RIGHTS THEY POUGNT\nAND DIED WHEN THE WAR\nWAS OVER THEY REFT ON\nFIGHTING.. THIS TIME FOR\nBETTER PAY, SHORTER HOURS.\nDECENT WORKING CONDITIONS.\nAND THE RIGHT TO VOTE\nWITHOUT OWNING A LOT OF\nproperty OR PAYING a poll\nJAX....S\nrated situation is the fact that\ngovernment stabilisation policy\nrefuses to reduce profits. If profit\nreduction was permissible, higher\nwages could be absorbed and\nhigher prices would not result.\n\nCONTROL OF supplies and in\nventories of basic materials to\nspeed reconversion appeared more\nprobable recently when President\nTruman told War Production Board\nto develop a program. Immediate\nly afterward such control appeared\nless likely again when WPB Chair\nman Krug said the President's or\nder changed nothing in WPB and\nhe was most impressed by the\nPresident\u2019s direction to remove\ncontrols when no longer necessary.\nWhether the President gets what\nhe wants on his front, or whether\nhe will have to fire Mr. Krug In\norder to get it, is a current subject\nof speculation. Reconversion boss\nJohn Snyder appears to have\nstepped into the breach just before\nV-J Day to smother the rash of de\ncontrol proposals that broke out at\nthat time.\n\nTHREATS TO price control grow\nmore menacing as manufacturers\nincrease their threats to hold back\nemployment unless they get the\nprices they want. OPA is grinding\nout generous new price formulas\nfor industries and individual firms\nA MCFPNG ROOM INSIDB A SO PULL Wg YWg KNOW Y VAUEV t COULD I\nTAV&W, H 75... POWW ALL J YOU'RE SOUNERSf)\\\nthe first smut in America took I' KBB3EEB3HBH|3BB^Z3EBB\nf I WANT TV CAST YSO Y THESE Y IS OUTRAGEOUS H WHO-\nMV VOTE FOR IDO FEL- 1 TH/3 EVER HEARD OF SUCH YOU'VE BEEN LISTENING U *S I I\nUNITED AUTOMOBILE WORKER\nto assure good profits early In the\nreconversion period.\nBui OPA mttt bo held guilty of\nevery delay fas re muyloyment.\nWith their control of news col*\nurans unchallenged by any con\ntrary statements from govern\nment, naannfSotnrirs are push\ning their advantage. OPA b ac\ncused of holding up reconversion\neven in cnees where the manu\nfacturer has net yet made ap\nplication for a reconversion price.\nHow strenuously this campaign\nis waged was indicated recently\nwhen some labor representatives\nhere expressed the belief that OPA\nis chief stumbling block to rapid re\nemployment. Apparently they had\nnot checked on Industry propagan\nda. Since July 18 OPA has had a\nregulation that permits manufac\nturers to compute their new price\nceilings and get going. Since early\nMay they have known how tlte pro\ngram was to work. They could\nhave been ready.\nIt has long been evident here\nthat industry would seek to line\nup labor as a champion for high\ner prices for employers. OPA it\nself baa abetted the scheme by\nreferring to Jobe as a reason for\nits various price-raising orders.\nGM in Good Shop*\nTwenty million dollars for re\nsearch, but not one cent for work\ners is the way the philosophy of\nthe GM Corporation works out.\nShortly after the corporation re\nfused demands of the UAW-CIO\nfor wage increases and for a guar\nanteed annual wage, C. E. Wilson,\npresident of GM, and tne nation\u2019s\nhighest salaried executive, an\nnounced the corporation\u2019s plans for\nestablishing a $20,000,000 research\ncenter in Detroit. Moreover, their\nfinancial situation is so good, due\nto the war, they plan a several\nhundred million dollar expansion\nprogram.\nBock Wages Paid\nOne hundred and eight Detroit\narea workers were paid $12,216.66\nin illegally withheld back wages in\nJuly, according to the Wage-Hour\nand Public Contracts Division, U. S.\nDepartment of Labor. Back-wage\ncollections in Michigan during the\nmonth totaled $22,114.34.\nRockford Workers\nTo Vote Soon\nROCKFORD, Hl.\u2014 Production and\nmaintenance employes, including\nwatchmen, truck drivers and labo\nratory testers, of the Rockford\nScrew Products Co., will vote for\nor against the UAW-CIO In an\nNLRB election to be held soon.\nReuther and Matthews Out\nWith Demands Upon 6M\nAnd Chrysler Coiporarions\nWage increases of 30 per cent have been demanded frron\nGeneral Motors and Chrysler by the UAW-CIO and similar in\ncreases will be sought from other employers as rapidly as con\ntract obligations permit.\nThe first demand was made by Walter P. Reuther, UAW-CIO\nvice-president and director of the anion\u2019s General Motors De\npartment, in a letter to GM President C. E. Wilson on August 18.\nReuther also urged Wilson to call\nan industry-wide conference to ne\ngotiate the increase on an industry\nbasis \u201cso there would be no prob\nlem of jockeying for competitive\nposition.** Ha stated that if such a\nconference were called the demand\non GM would be withdrawn in fa\nvor of an industry-wide demand by\nthe UAW-CIO.\nPresident R. J. Thomas an\nnounced that similar wage de\nmands would be made on other\ncorporations as rapidly as con\ntract requirements permit, and\nNorman Matthews, director of\nthe union's Chrysler department,\npresented a 30 per cent wage In\ncrease demand on the Chrysler\nCorporation.\nNegotiations with Ford had been\nin progress, headed by Richard T.\nLeonard, UAW-CIO national Ford\ndirector, when Japan surrendered,\nand werfc adjourned then for 30\ndays.\nREUTHER POINTED out to\nWilson that the new wage policy\nannounced by President Truman\nfor the reconversion period permits\nwage increases so long as they do\nnot necessitate price increases. He\ndeclared the UAW-CIO in hearty\naccord with this policy.\nThe wage demands served upon\nthe GM Corporation by the UAW\nCIO, include:\n1. A 30 per cent increase in the\npresent scheduled hourly rates of\nall GM employes covered by the\nAgreement.\na. Application for an appropri\nate part of this increase to a\ncorporation-wide equalization\nfund, which shall be utilized to\nachieve uniform wage rates\nthroughout the corporation.\n\"Any variation from the principle\nof equal pay for equal work re\ngardless of geographical location,\"\nReuther said, \"cannot be justified\non an economic or moral basis in a\ncorporation which fixes national\nuniform prices for its cars regard\nless of where manufactured.\"\nb. The creation of a Social Se\ncurity Fund by allocating a por\ntion of the 30 per cent increase\nfor this purpose, equal to three\nper cent of the total payroll of\nthe employes covered by the GM\nUAW agreement.\nThe demand for a Social Security\nprogram for auto workers was\nadopted as official policy of the\nUAW-CIO at the last meeting of\nthe international executive board\nin Minneapolis.\na\nThe profit and reserve position\nof the GM Corporation, Reuther\nsaid, provides ample margin for\nabsorbing the wage adjustment\nwithout necessitating price In\ncreases.\n\u201cThis corporation has been de\nscribed by the Federal Trade Com\nmission as the moot profitable cor\nporation in the history of the\nworld. It has done very well for\nitself since it has had Uncle Sam\nas its principle customer. With the\nslogan, \u2018Victory Is Our Business/\nGM\u2019s profits in 1944 before taxes\nwere $435,409,024. That Is 78 per\ncent more than the yearly average\nprofits of $244,779,268 for 1936-39.\u2019*\nMoreover, Reuther pointed out,\nthe corporation\u2019s net worth had in\ncreased 22 per cent during the war.\nLabor productivity has Increased\nsharply as well, he said, wiiile the\ncorporation has available to it\nfrom the government many mil\nlions in cash refunds ou excess\nprofits taxes and additional refunds\nin the event that profits fall below\nprewar levels.\n\"Contrast this with the eco\nnomic position of the GM work\ner,\" said Reuther. \"For thou\nsands of them peace already has\nbrought total unemployment,\nwhile for the fortunate remain\nder war\u2019s end must mean a 30\nper eent cut in take-home pay\nwith the resumption of the 40-\nhour week.\nSerious deflation. Mr. Reuther\nwarned, would be the inevitable\nresult if workers\u2019 take-home pay,\nwhich has been reduced 30 per cent\nby reduction to a 40-hour week, is\nnot maintained.\nPAGE 3","height":"25317","width":"17286"}}
